[1]
Date: 09 May 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters, 5 May 2002 [edited]

Poland closes in on source of first BSE case
--------------------------------------------
After a massive 2-day search, Polish officials on Sun 5 May 2002
located the place where the country's first case of mad cow disease may
have originated, but are still unsure how the animal got infected.
Before this weekend's revelation that a cow slaughtered near the Slovak
border was contaminated, Poland had been considered a "low-risk" country
for bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), believed to cause the deadly
human Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease. Inadequate documentation about the
9-year-old cow's history forced police and veterinary services to conduct a
village-by-village search before tracing its origin to the tiny farming
community of Swiebodzin.
"We still have to establish the animal's genealogy and what it was fed,"
the chief veterinarian of southern Malopolska province Krzysztof Ankiewicz
told a news conference in the region's capital, Krakow. No other diseased
animal had been found so far but 3 other cows in the same abattoir had also
been destroyed as a precaution, officials said. It was not clear whether
any livestock in Swiebodzin would be isolated or slaughtered.
The labor-intensive search illustrated the problems caused by Poland's
antiquated agricultural infrastructure less [than] 2 years before the
country is expected to join the European Union. "The present livestock
tagging system does not meet European Union requirements," Piotr Kolodziej,
Poland's chief veterinarian, told reporters. "In the EU an animal can be
identified in a matter of minutes." Poland has delayed implementing EU
livestock identification norms due to logistical problems and poor
planning. "The introduction of a proper identification system and creation
of a database should get under way this year and be completed by the end of
2003," Kolodziej said.
More than 100 people, most in Britain, have died or are believed to be
suffering from Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease, which is thought to be caused by
eating contaminated meat products. [According to the official UK figures,
their number was 121 on 6 May 2002.- Mod.AS] But no fatalities have been
reported in Poland, eastern Europe's biggest farm economy. Poland, an
exporter of beef, checks every cow older than 30 months old for BSE when it
is slaughtered, but animals are not always closely monitored from the
moment of their birth as is the case in the EU. The European Commission
wrote in a report in February that it was concerned about the ability of
Poland to detect BSE and contain the disease from spreading if an outbreak
occurred.
[Byline: Wojciech Zurawski]
