Date: 10 May 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties (OIE) 10 May 2002 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_72.HTM#Sec1>

Bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) in Poland
-------------------------------------------------
(Disease never previously reported in Poland).
Information received on 6 May 2002 from Dr Piotr Kolodziej, Chief Veterinary
Officer, Ministry of Agriculture and Food Economy, Warsaw:
Report date: 6 May 2002.
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 2 May 2002.
Outbreaks:
Location : province of Little Poland (Malopolskie), in the south of the
country
No. of outbreaks: 1
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
Species bov
Susceptible: 3
Cases:1
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 3
Slaughtered: 0
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratories where diagnosis was made:
- BSE regional laboratory in Cracow (Krakow);
- National Veterinary Institute in Pulawy (BSE national reference
laboratory).
B. Diagnostic tests used: Bio-Rad Laboratories Platelia test;
immunoblotting.
Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown.
******
[3]
Date: 09 May 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: PAP news agency, Warsaw, in English, 07 May 2002 [edited]

Poland's neighbors ban beef imports after BSE detection
---------------------------------------------------------
Veterinary authorities of Ukraine and Estonia have banned beef
imports from Poland after the first BSE case was detected in Poland Sat 4
May 2002, according to Ukraynsky Novyny agency and the Polish embassy in
Tallinn.
Ukraine banned imports of beef from Poland for 5 years. The ban on Polish
beef has also been imposed by Lithuania and Russia. Russia additionally
banned, until further notice, imports of lamb and meat of ruminants.
Also Romania joined the group of countries that put the ban on imports of
Polish beef, according to the Romanian Agriculture Ministry.
On Monday, Tarnow [southern Poland] prosecutor's office accused 2 men
apprehended in connection with BSE detection of falsifying documentation on
the sick cow.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The identification of BSE in Poland should not be overly surprising. The
EU Scientific Steering Committee adopted on 30 Mar 2001 its opinion on the
"Geographical Risk of Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (GBR)" in Poland,
stating that "it is likely but not confirmed that one or several cattle
that are (pre-clinically or clinically) infected with the BSE agent are
currently present in the domestic herd of Poland (GBR III)". The main
reason for that assessment was the fact that Poland was exposed to an
"extremely high" external challenge since 1991, mainly due to massive
imports of meat and bone meal (MBM) from BSE-affected countries. This
import was in the range of 1 700 000 tonnes in total, of which around 1 000
000 tonnes was from Germany, and the rest mainly from Denmark and the
Netherlands. In addition, the GBR report indicated that feeding MBM to
cattle was legally possible until March 1997 and likely to have occurred.
Rendering was a common practice in Poland, the raw materials for which
include specific risk materials (SRM) and condemned organs from slaughtered
ruminants and a limited amount of fallen stock. Active surveillance for BSE
started in 2001. The report concluded: "Given the very unstable system and
the fact that the BSE-agent is likely to be already present in the
country, it is assumed that the GBR is increasing".
About 100 000 BSE tests have been carried out, so far, in Polish cattle (see
ref. below). The total cattle population of Poland (OIE yearbook, 2000) is
approx. 6 million head. The testing rate (in healthy adult animals) in most
EU countries was significantly higher during 2001 (total national cattle
population in millions, from same source: France - 2 382 225 (20.0);
Germany - 2 565 341 (14.5); Ireland - 636 930 (7.2); the Netherlands - 454
649 (4.0).
Additional information on the results of the epidemiological investigations
in Poland, with special reference to the source of infection, will be very
helpful. - Mod.AS]
